\begin_layout Subsection
Diffusion MRI Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Define dMRI
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Use Derek Jones' book.
 Use Maxime's paper HARDI.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a Fourier relationship between the signal attenuation and the diffusion
 propagator such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\vec{q},t\right)=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{3}}p\left(\vec{r},t\right)exp\left(-2\pi i\vec{q}^{T}\vec{r}\right)d\vec{r}\label{eq:FFT-relationship}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\mathbf{q},t\right)=\int_{\mathbb{R}^{3}}p\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)exp\left(-2\pi i\mathbf{q}^{T}\mathbf{r}\right)d\mathbf{r}\label{eq:FFT-relationship-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
State-of-the-art
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Diffusion Spectrum Imaging
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Diffusion Spectrum Imaging (DSI) can detect the multiple fascicle orientation
 within a voxel.
 DSI is sensible to crossing fibers in the voxel.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Q-Ball Imaging
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Funk-Radon transform (FRT) is employed on HARDI derived data to obtain
 a diffusion ODF (dODF)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Psi\left(\mathbf{u}\right)=\int_{\varOmega\left(\mathbf{u}\right)}S\left(\mathbf{q},t\right)d\mathbf{q},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varOmega\left(\mathbf{u}\right)=\left\{ \mathbf{q}\in\mathbb{S}^{2}\,|\,\mathbf{q}\perp\mathbf{u}\right\} $
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{q}=$
\end_inset

.
 FRT uses the fact that the diffusion signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is maximal in the directions perpendicular to the underlying fascicles,
 see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:funk-radon-transform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-funk-radon-transform.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:funk-radon-transform"

\end_inset

Illustration of the FRT that QBI uses to reconstruct the dODF using the
 diffusion MRI measured signal.
 Image taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HARDI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The dODF can properly represent the presence and orientation of multiple
 crossing fascicles.
 However, the resulted dODF is artificially smooth and inflated compared
 to the true diffusion ODF.
 Problematically, this same feature causes q-ball to poorly distinguish
 fibers crossing at tight angles.
 Some modifications to QBI have been published.
 For example, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "QBI-SWT"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was proposed a spherical wavelet transform to sharpen and denoise the dODF.
 Additionally, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "QBI-CSA"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 the dODF is normalized using a solid angle factor.
 Finally, in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GQI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 a generalization of the q-ball imaging was proposed using a direct transform
 of the raw signal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Diffusion Orientation Transform
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Diffusion Orientation Transform (DOT) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DOT"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is a technique that provideds a direct estimation of displacement probability
 surfaces at each voxel from the dMRI data.
 It transforms water diffusivity profiles into displacement probability
 profiles.
 DOT uses the Fourier relationship between the signal attenuation and te
 diffusion propagator 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(\mathbf{r},t\right)=\oint_{\varOmega}\int_{0}^{\infty}E\left(\mathbf{q},t\right)exp\left(-2\pi iqt\mathbf{q}^{T}\mathbf{r}\right)dqd\mathbf{q}
\]

\end_inset

DOT assumes that 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 attenuates mono-exponentially
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(\mathbf{q},t\right)=exp\left(-4\pi^{2}tq^{2}D\left(\mathbf{q}\right)\right),
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is the apparent diffusion coefficient or diffusivity profile.
 DOT faces some limitations regarding the HARDI sampling schemes with finite
 support, truncated spherical harmonics and the mono-exponential attenuation.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DOT-revisited"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was proposed an extension of the DOT method that mitigates the DOT limitations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
STD
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Constrained Spherical Deconvolution (CSD)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Spherical Deconvolution (SD) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SD"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 is one of the most popular techniques to recover the principal diffusion
 directions from the dMRI data.
 SD considers the HARDI signal 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 as the convolution of the response function, which is an axially symmetric
 kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 that represents a single-fiber response, with the expected true fiber orientati
on distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

, known as fODF.
 Given the measurements of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 along all the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 gradient directions , the fODF can be reconstructed by solving the following
 optimization problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\underset{F}{min}\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\bigl\Vert S\left(\mathbf{g}_{i},b\right)-S_{0}\int_{\mathbb{S}^{2}}F\left(\mathbf{v}\right)R\left(\mathbf{g}_{i},\mathbf{v}\right)d\mathbf{v}\bigr\Vert^{2},\label{eq:spherical-deconvolution}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-spherical-deconvolution-a.png
	scale 40

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\;\;\;$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-spherical-deconvolution-b.png
	scale 35

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SD"

\end_inset

Imagen taken from 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HARDI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This SD technique is ill-posed and affected by noise.
 Later in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CSD"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 was introduced a modification to SD called Constrained Spherical Deconvolution
 (CSD) that preserves the angular resolution while remaining robust to noise
 effects.
 In CSD a non-negativity constraint on the estimated fODF is included into
 the formulation, as negative fibre orientation densities are physically
 impossible.
 Besides, this constraint eliminates the need for low-pass filtering the
 obtained fODF.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
DBF
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Multi-Tensor
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Multi-tensor representation is a natural extension of the the Diffusion
 Tensor Imaging (DTI) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DTI"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where orientated diffusion along the fascicles is represented with a mixture
 of Gaussian distributions such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{i}\left(v\right)=\sum_{k=1}^{M}\alpha_{k}exp\left(-b\mathbf{g}_{i}^{T}D_{k}\left(v\right)\mathbf{g}_{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Problem Statement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Classical measures like FA with DTI are very sensitive to white matter anomalies
 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
add ref 14,15,16 from Mitacs
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 However, it is now very well-known that FA is not specific, i.e.
 several different microstructure scenarios may lead to the same FA, see
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:different-FA-scenarios"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 For example, FA of 0.4 is possible from a crossing fiber voxel, but it is
 also possible to obtain that FA from a single fiber population demyelinating
 (going from FA of ~0.7 to 0.4) or from a voxel in that has partial volume
 with a CSF, or isotropic freewater from neuroinflammation contaminating
 the voxel leading to a drop of a high FA voxel to a low FA of 0.4 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
add refs 19,20,21,22,23 of Mitacs
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename fig-different-FA-scenarios.png
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:different-FA-scenarios"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is thus clear that each fascicle that traverses a voxel should have its
 fiber-specific FA and diffusivities, or fascicle-FA, recently also coined
 fixel-based FA (a fixel is a fiber element) 
\begin_inset Note Comment
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
add ref 24 from Mitacs
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Fixel-based analysis needs to be translated to neurodegenerative diseases
 and this is still a very important open problem.
\end_layout

